00:45:14,170 --> 00:45:17,010
♪♪ with me ♪♪♪♪

825
00:45:27,110 --> 00:45:30,060
No, I never agreed
to Bruce Grossman
as our manager.

826
00:45:30,100 --> 00:45:31,080
I don't trust him.

827
00:45:31,120 --> 00:45:33,110
The guy is just a--

828
00:45:33,150 --> 00:45:35,060
he got the stones
over a million dollar
advance at a Decker.

829
00:45:35,100 --> 00:45:37,080
We never got any advance.

830
00:45:37,120 --> 00:45:40,060
Yeah, he also got
all the hot rock songs
off them, too, John.

831
00:45:40,100 --> 00:45:42,230
Look, why don't we have
Lee and John eastman
handle our affairs?

832
00:45:43,030 --> 00:45:45,030
No one knows
the music business
better than they do.

833
00:45:45,070 --> 00:45:46,110
Press announcement
already went out

834
00:45:46,150 --> 00:45:48,020
naming Grossman
as our manager.

835
00:45:48,060 --> 00:45:49,180
Well, get it back.
He's-- he's got problems

836
00:45:49,220 --> 00:45:51,040
with the u.S.
Tax authorities.

837
00:45:51,080 --> 00:45:53,000
Just exactly
what we don't need.

838
00:45:53,040 --> 00:45:54,030
Yoko and I want him.

839
00:45:54,070 --> 00:45:55,170
He's blunt, he's funny,

840
00:45:55,210 --> 00:45:57,230
he knows every one
of our songs.

841
00:45:58,030 --> 00:46:00,040
And none of US are
married to his sister.

842
00:46:00,080 --> 00:46:01,180
Got to sign now, mate.

843
00:46:01,220 --> 00:46:03,180
He's flying back
to New York tomorrow.

844
00:46:03,220 --> 00:46:05,210
Needs a signed contract
to give back to his board.

845
00:46:06,010 --> 00:46:07,070
Oh, now wait.
Wait a second.

846
00:46:07,110 --> 00:46:09,050
Board? What board?

847
00:46:11,080 --> 00:46:12,140
Oh, great.

848
00:46:13,070 --> 00:46:15,060
Wonderful.

849
00:46:15,100 --> 00:46:16,180
What am I gonna tell
the eastmans, eh?

850
00:46:16,220 --> 00:46:18,170
They can still be
our lawyers.

851
00:46:18,210 --> 00:46:20,230
We want Bruce
to handle the money.

852
00:46:22,100 --> 00:46:25,050
Yeah, well,
screw 20% for a start.
He'll take 15.

853
00:46:25,090 --> 00:46:26,160
He's got to have 20.

854
00:46:26,200 --> 00:46:29,050
It can wait
till Monday then.

855
00:46:29,090 --> 00:46:32,050
I want my lawyer
to have a look at it.
You're just stalling.

856
00:46:32,090 --> 00:46:35,100
Did you sign, Ringo?
We all signed.
It's up to you, mate.

857
00:46:37,050 --> 00:46:40,040
So I'm outvoted.
That's it.
All right, fine.

858
00:46:40,080 --> 00:46:42,070
You don't need
my bloody signature
then, do you?

859
00:46:42,110 --> 00:46:44,040
Hey, man.

860
00:46:44,080 --> 00:46:46,030
We'll do it without you.

861
00:46:55,060 --> 00:46:58,130
(Linda) Those days
at Abby road were
frustrating for everybody.

862
00:46:58,170 --> 00:47:01,140
Weeks went by without
anything getting done.

863
00:47:04,010 --> 00:47:05,220
He's not coming.

864
00:47:06,020 --> 00:47:07,230
We're never going
to finish.

865
00:47:12,050 --> 00:47:13,140
Right.

866
00:47:15,100 --> 00:47:17,080
Let's pack it in.

867
00:47:18,060 --> 00:47:20,070
What is it
with you and John?

868
00:47:20,110 --> 00:47:21,170
What's the game?

869
00:47:21,210 --> 00:47:24,090
(Pianist) What do you
want me to do?

870
00:47:24,130 --> 00:47:25,220
We're mates.

871
00:47:26,020 --> 00:47:27,150
We're supposed
to hang together.

872
00:47:27,190 --> 00:47:30,130
We'll, uh, we'll try
and sort it out.
We'll get it soon.

873
00:47:30,170 --> 00:47:32,140
It's ok.

874
00:47:32,180 --> 00:47:34,160
(Linda) Things didn't
get any better
between Paul and John.

875
00:47:34,200 --> 00:47:37,130
But for US,
life was wonderful.

876
00:47:37,170 --> 00:47:40,160
Our child was born
just before
our 2nd anniversary.

877
00:47:40,200 --> 00:47:43,080
Her name was Mary
after Paul's mother.

878
00:47:43,120 --> 00:47:44,210
♪♪♪♪[Music box playing]

879
00:47:46,230 --> 00:47:49,110
Good. Good girl.

880
00:47:49,150 --> 00:47:52,100
Oh, that's beautiful, baby.
Go help your father.

881
00:47:56,150 --> 00:47:58,080
[Banging on door]

882
00:48:02,060 --> 00:48:03,070
John.

883
00:48:03,110 --> 00:48:05,020
Where is he?
John.

884
00:48:05,060 --> 00:48:06,170
McCartney!

885
00:48:08,030 --> 00:48:09,140
What the bloody hell
are you playing at?

886
00:48:09,180 --> 00:48:11,140
We booked a session,
didn't we?

887
00:48:11,180 --> 00:48:13,060
[Baby crying]
Ringo, George and I have
been cooling our arses

888
00:48:13,100 --> 00:48:15,030
for two bloody hours
in the studio,

889
00:48:15,070 --> 00:48:16,140
and you don't have
the bleeding decency
to show up.

890
00:48:16,180 --> 00:48:18,200
Oh, like you've
never kept me waiting.

891
00:48:19,000 --> 00:48:21,210
What about US
out there, eh?
What about US?

892
00:48:22,010 --> 00:48:23,090
Why didn't you tell US
you couldn't make it?

893
00:48:23,130 --> 00:48:24,200
So I'm sorry, all right!

894
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:27,070
Lin and I were celebrating
our anniversary!

895
00:48:32,070 --> 00:48:33,060
[Glass shattering]

896
00:48:33,100 --> 00:48:34,080
[Baby crying]

897
00:48:34,120 --> 00:48:36,120
Hey! John.

898
00:48:36,160 --> 00:48:38,140
Happy anniversary, mate.

899
00:48:42,090 --> 00:48:44,060
[Door slamming]

900
00:48:44,100 --> 00:48:47,160
(Mason) The cancer
has shown up in
your other breast here.

901
00:48:48,200 --> 00:48:50,110
So, what, it's spreading?

902
00:48:50,150 --> 00:48:54,100
Not necessarily.
It's possibly
a new cancer.

903
00:48:54,140 --> 00:48:58,010
So what now?
More radiation?
More chemo?

904
00:48:58,140 --> 00:49:00,030
I'm sorry.

905
00:49:01,020 --> 00:49:02,090
Oh.

906
00:49:03,080 --> 00:49:05,100
So what do I tell people?

907
00:49:05,140 --> 00:49:08,040
I've been saying that
eating veggie reduces
your risk of cancer.

908
00:49:08,080 --> 00:49:10,080
Don't worry about that now.

909
00:49:10,120 --> 00:49:12,100
They'll feel deceived.

910
00:49:12,140 --> 00:49:14,130
Lin, the most important
thing right now is
to get you better.

911
00:49:14,170 --> 00:49:16,120
Now, we, uh,
we read about

912
00:49:16,160 --> 00:49:18,100
this experimental
bone marrow treatment
in California.

913
00:49:18,140 --> 00:49:19,220
50% remission
rates, right?

914
00:49:20,020 --> 00:49:21,140
Unconfirmed statistics.

915
00:49:21,180 --> 00:49:24,050
The procedure
needs more testing
before we know.

916
00:49:24,090 --> 00:49:26,030
But you could do it here?

917
00:49:26,070 --> 00:49:29,050
Only if you take part
in randomized
clinical trials.

918
00:49:29,090 --> 00:49:30,090
It's our policy.

919
00:49:30,130 --> 00:49:32,120
Randomized, meaning?

920
00:49:32,160 --> 00:49:34,230
You're assigned either
to a control group
getting standard chemo

921
00:49:35,030 --> 00:49:37,030
or to the experimental
treatment group.

922
00:49:37,070 --> 00:49:39,140
Like a Guinea pig.
So we have
no choice about it?

923
00:49:39,180 --> 00:49:41,080
It has to be random.

924
00:49:41,120 --> 00:49:43,170
But if it's lin's best shot,
can't we just pay for it

925
00:49:43,210 --> 00:49:45,060
if we want
the experimental
treatment?

926
00:49:45,100 --> 00:49:48,020
There are other places
that do it, yes.

927
00:49:48,060 --> 00:49:49,140
Not here.
Not until we know
it works.

928
00:49:54,100 --> 00:49:57,030
There are serious risks.
The dosage is lethal.

929
00:49:57,070 --> 00:50:00,010
It kills off
your bone marrow
which must be replaced.

930
00:50:00,050 --> 00:50:02,110
It's a long
difficult ordeal, and
there's no guarantee

931
00:50:02,150 --> 00:50:04,090
it's any better than
what we're already doing.

932
00:50:04,130 --> 00:50:06,120
(Receptionist)
Dr. Mason's office.

933
00:50:07,180 --> 00:50:09,220
Dr. Mason,
they're ready for you.

934
00:50:10,020 --> 00:50:11,190
Think it over
and let me know.

935
00:50:12,170 --> 00:50:14,190
Right. Thanks.

936
00:50:17,220 --> 00:50:20,080
Oh, it's a bloody
crap shoot
is what it is.

937
00:50:21,010 --> 00:50:22,150
No.

938
00:50:22,190 --> 00:50:25,210
We'll go. We'll go to la.
We'll get the treatment.

939
00:50:26,230 --> 00:50:28,230
What have we
got to lose?

940
00:50:30,170 --> 00:50:32,100
Everything.

941
00:50:32,140 --> 00:50:34,230
(Paul) So are we gonna
continue as
a group or not?

942
00:50:35,030 --> 00:50:37,050
Listen, lads.
We've got to get back
to performing.

943
00:50:37,090 --> 00:50:39,140
It's been three years
since we were
last on the stage.

944
00:50:39,180 --> 00:50:42,110
I can't see US doing
massive big shows again.

945
00:50:42,150 --> 00:50:45,110
Ok. So, so we'll go
back to small clubs.

946
00:50:45,150 --> 00:50:47,220
(George) The Beatles.
Impossible.

947
00:50:48,020 --> 00:50:49,150
Right. We could
go unannounced.

948
00:50:49,190 --> 00:50:52,150
We-- we could go in disguise.
Change your name.

949
00:50:52,190 --> 00:50:54,150
[Chuckling]
There's a thought.
What a trip.

950
00:50:55,070 --> 00:50:56,170
I think you're daft.

951
00:50:58,080 --> 00:50:59,090
I'm not supposed
to tell you,

952
00:50:59,130 --> 00:51:00,180
but I'm leaving
the group.

953
00:51:03,180 --> 00:51:05,030
Come on, yoko.

954
00:51:10,100 --> 00:51:11,210
John.

955
00:51:19,040 --> 00:51:21,080
(Paul) It's the end
of the Beatles.

956
00:51:21,120 --> 00:51:23,120
Without John,
there's no group.

957
00:51:23,160 --> 00:51:25,140
But it's not
the end of apple.

958
00:51:25,180 --> 00:51:27,040
It's the only job
I've ever had.

959
00:51:27,080 --> 00:51:29,170
We got to find a way
to cut you loose.

960
00:51:29,210 --> 00:51:31,100
Under the contract
you signed,

961
00:51:31,140 --> 00:51:33,060
apple owns
everything you make,

962
00:51:33,100 --> 00:51:36,020
every song you write
for the next seven years.

963
00:51:36,060 --> 00:51:37,180
Even if the band
breaks up?

964
00:51:37,220 --> 00:51:40,100
And Grossman gets 20%.

965
00:51:40,140 --> 00:51:43,110
Oh, you know
I never even signed
with the bastard.

966
00:51:43,150 --> 00:51:45,130
Oh, we can sue
to break the contract.

967
00:51:45,170 --> 00:51:48,230
They'll never let you
out of it voluntarily.

968
00:51:49,030 --> 00:51:51,190
[Sighing] All right, fine.
Great. Let's do it.

969
00:51:51,230 --> 00:51:53,230
Yeah, stick it to him.

970
00:51:54,030 --> 00:51:57,150
You can't sue Grossman.
He wasn't party
to the apple agreement.

971
00:51:57,190 --> 00:52:00,110
You have to sue
to dissolve
the partnership.

972
00:52:00,150 --> 00:52:04,010
Sue John, George, Ringo?
No, I can't do that. No.

973
00:52:05,040 --> 00:52:06,160
It's the only way, Paul.

974
00:52:08,040 --> 00:52:09,120
(Judge) In view of
the tangled state

975
00:52:09,160 --> 00:52:11,080
of the Beatles
financial affairs,

976
00:52:11,120 --> 00:52:13,170
the unconvincing testimony
of Mr. Bruce Grossman,

977
00:52:13,210 --> 00:52:17,160
and the absence of staff
capable of giving
necessary direction,

978
00:52:17,200 --> 00:52:20,140
the court grants
the petition of
Mr. Paul McCartney

979
00:52:20,180 --> 00:52:24,090
and appoints a receiver
to take over the running
of the partnership

980
00:52:24,130 --> 00:52:26,110
until a full trail
can be held to determine

981
00:52:26,150 --> 00:52:29,190
the long-term disposition
of the Beatles company.

982
00:52:40,060 --> 00:52:41,130
[Dog barking]

983
00:52:41,170 --> 00:52:45,040
McCartney, who the hell
do you think you are?

984
00:53:15,170 --> 00:53:18,060
(Woman)
Dr. Hunter to radiology.

985
00:53:18,100 --> 00:53:20,100
Dr. Hunter to radiology.

986
00:53:27,000 --> 00:53:29,000
Ok, now,
you ready for this?

987
00:53:30,100 --> 00:53:32,080
All right, hang on.

988
00:53:34,070 --> 00:53:35,110
Anyone we know?

989
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:40,130
Oh, look.
Here's trouble.

990
00:53:40,170 --> 00:53:42,230
Hello, love.
How you doing?

991
00:53:43,030 --> 00:53:45,040
Hello, beautiful.

992
00:53:45,080 --> 00:53:48,200
Something I made for you.
Presies. Great.

993
00:53:50,100 --> 00:53:51,170
Oh.

994
00:53:53,170 --> 00:53:55,090
Oh, Heather.

995
00:53:56,140 --> 00:53:58,000
It's beautiful.

996
00:53:58,040 --> 00:53:59,160
It's a medicine jar.

997
00:53:59,200 --> 00:54:02,060
A hopi design.
Mmm-hmm.

998
00:54:02,100 --> 00:54:05,230
This is amazing.
Look at the detailing.

999
00:54:06,030 --> 00:54:09,080
Look at this, Paul.
Yeah, it's amazing.

1000
00:54:09,120 --> 00:54:11,190
Come here.
Give me a kiss,
talented girl.

1001
00:54:13,210 --> 00:54:17,190
Heather, I just want
you to know that
if anything goes wrong--

1002
00:54:17,230 --> 00:54:19,190
it won't, will it?
You said not to worry.

1003
00:54:19,230 --> 00:54:21,200
Yes, I did,
and-- and I meant that.

1004
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:26,090
